  <body>
    <div xml:id="PN324">
      <lg type="edition">
<l>verukkuviṭai yaṉṉa vekuṇōkkuk kayantalaip</l>
<l>puḷḷūṉ ṟiṉṟa pulavunāṟu kayavāy</l>
<l>veḷvāy vēṭṭuvar vīḻtuṇai makāar</l>
<l>ciṟiyilai yuṭaiyiṉ curaiyuṭai vāṉmu</l>
<l>ḷūka nuṇkōṟ ceṟitta vampiṉ</l>
<l>valāar valviṟ kulāvarak kōlip</l>
<l>parutti vēlik karuppai pārkkum</l>
<l>puṉpulan taḻīiya vaṅkuṭic cīṟūrk</l>
<l>kumiḻuṇ veḷḷai pakuvāy peyartta</l>
<l>veṇkāḻ tāya vaṇkāṟ pantar</l>
<l>iṭaiyaṉ pottiya ciṟutī viḷakkattup</l>
<l>pāṇarō ṭirunta nāṇuṭai neṭuntakai</l>
<l>valampaṭu tāṉai vēntaṟ</l>
<l>kulantuḻi yulakku neñcaṟi tuṇaiyē.</l>
</lg>
<lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>In the little village with pretty homes that encompasses low/grassy fields,</l>
<l>where with [their] chosen companions the sons of the hunters with white mouths(?),</l>
<l>soft mouths reeking of flesh that have eaten bird’s meat </l>
<l>[and] soft heads with glances angry as those of the wild tomcat,</l>
<l>form into bends [their] strong Valāar-wood bows</l>
<l>with arrows on which are tightened with fine Ūkam-grass stalk</l>
<l>the [sharp-]tipped white thorns of the small-leaved Uṭai tree</l>
<l>[and] look out for wild rats in the cotton fence,</l>
<l>The paragon who possesses shame [of defeat] who sits with the bards</l>
<l>by the lamp with small fire covered by the goatherd</l>
<l>in the arbour on pretty stilts where are spread the white kernels</l>
<l>ejected from the split mouth of the Kumiḻ-eating white goat,</l>
<l>is the companion familiar to the heart of the king</l>
<l>with a victorious army, who will die when he dies.</l>
</lg>
    </div>
  </body>
</text>
